<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-mjEIENY5be9iCbQ8w7bR6Q" name="infrastructure_gap_analysis,_-v5XsDDHEdyz_pzDMsV8FQ" guid="-mjEIENY5be9iCbQ8w7bR6Q" changeDate="2007-11-08T21:42:37.000-0800" version="v.2">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This artifact identifies the gaps between the IT organization's existing technology, applications, processes, skills&#xD;
    and organization and those required to implement and support the new system.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; This is comprised of the&#xD;
    findings of a data gathering process, or a comparative design exercise. It quantifies the impact of the migration from&#xD;
    the existing to the desired IT infrastructure.&amp;nbsp; The artifact documents the work done to date, what was found&#xD;
    during data gathering (high level requirements and key assumptions), the difference between current and future&#xD;
    infrastructure and the steps needed to deal with the gaps.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <keyConsiderations>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following guidance is suggested:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        If an architecture for the new system has been created, compare this to the current IT environment of the&#xD;
        enterprise to identify gaps.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Wherever possible use existing inventories and application portfolios and compare these with system documentation.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></keyConsiderations>
  <purpose>This artifact is used to plan the activities needed to build and support the future IT infrastructure.</purpose>
  <impactOfNotHaving>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Not having this artifact may result in one or more of the following occurring:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The technical team may focus only on the server hardware and not pay attention to the enterprise-wide&#xD;
        implementation and support issues.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The stakeholders may not understand potential pitfalls in implementing the new infrastructure.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Stakeholder resources and skills could be inadequate.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Consensus building with the technical team may not occur.&amp;nbsp; They may not become aware of issues affecting other&#xD;
        departments.&amp;nbsp; Without education and consensus:&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li style=&quot;LIST-STYLE-TYPE: none&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Identification and prioritization of issues does not occur.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Ownership of&amp;nbsp; the action plans required to address gaps does not occur.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                No management awareness of the identified gaps and, therefore, no decision making on how to address them.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>&lt;p>&#xD;
    It may not be appropriate to produce this artifact if:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        This is a green-field site or project with no existing infrastructure.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An existing application is being replaced with a new one and experience shows no reason for a gap analysis.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The existing infrastructure is being completely replaced.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></reasonsForNotNeeding>
  <briefOutline>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Infrastructure Gap Analysis is basically textual, with tables or spreadsheets showing the facts, findings and&#xD;
    conclusions. Subject areas or headings that could be used as categorizations include:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technology, Process and People - this categorizes the subject area of the analysis.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Facts, Assumptions, Questions and Issues - this sub-categorizes the subject areas into what is known, what is&#xD;
        assumed, what needs to be known and what is an issue.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        End User Function Groups - this is a categorization of the organization into functional areas (e.g. manufacturing,&#xD;
        sales, marketing development etc) with a list of the infrastructure used. Sub-categorizations of end user function&#xD;
        groups could include:&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li style=&quot;LIST-STYLE-TYPE: none&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Number of Users&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Service level objective(s)&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Existing hardware and software&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Required hardware and software&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Connectivity&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Redundancy requirements&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Central vs. local applications&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Interfaces&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></briefOutline>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
